Description.val:
The AIM-9X Sidewinder short-range air-to-air missile is a long term evolution of the AIM-9 series of fielded missiles.  The AIM-9X missile program provides a launch and leave, air combat munition that uses passive infrared (IR) energy for acquisition and tracking of enemy aircraft and complements the Advanced Medium Range Air-to-Air missile (AMRAAM).  Air superiority in the short-range air-to-air missile arena is essential and includes first shot, first kill opportunity against an enemy employing IR countermeasures.  The AIM-9X employs several components common with the AIM-9M (fuze, rocket motor and warhead).  Anti-Tamper features have been incorporated to protect improvements inherent in this design.

[P5 / MISSILE]: AIM-9X is a Post Milestone III, Acquisition Category IC (ACAT-IC) joint service program with Navy lead. In June 2011, the Milestone Decision Authority (MDA) established the AIM-9X Block II missile program which was approved for entry at Milestone C for Low Rate Initial Production (LRIP). The 2366 A/B certification and Acquisition Program Baseline for AIM-9X Block II was signed December 23, 2011, and the Block I program was terminated.

Justification.val:
FY16 provides funding to procure the second lot of Full Rate Production (FRP) AIM-9X Block II missiles.

Total Program quantity by service:
The US Navy will procure 3,937 total missiles under this Budget Line Item: 1,289 Block I missiles and 2,648 Block II missiles.  In addition, the US Navy procured 63 Block I missiles in FY 2001 under the AIM-9M Modification program.
The US Air Force will procure 5,030 total missiles under this Budget Line Item: 1,678 Block I missiles and 3,352 Block II missiles.  In addition, the US Air Force procured 67 Block I missiles in FY 2001 under the AIM-9M Modification program.

Totals include funding for Program Number 581, Tactical Air Intercept/AIM-9X Block I, as well as Program Number 442, Tactical Air Intercept/AIM-9X Block II.

Remarks.val: [Flyaway] The FY14 Contract was signed on 25 June 2014 and procures the last lot of Low Rate Initial Production (LRIP).

Name.@footnote: The FY 2014 Unit cost reflects actual Foreign Military Sales (FMS) quantity of 256 missiles. Missile unit cost decrease in FY15 and FY16 (from PB15 to PB16) reflects updated cost model projections based upon final negotiated Lot 14 contract award. Unit costs decreases from FY15 to FY16 reflect increased quantities and the agreed upon Forward Pricing Rate Agreement (FPRA). FY15 through FY20 unit cost assumes FMS quantities estimated at 80 missiles per year.   AUR unit cost increase from FY16 to FY17 is due to incorporating the Block II Plus missile configuration into production.  AUR unit cost increase from FY18 to FY19 is due to the significant quantity decreases: FY18 total quantity (USN, USAF & FMS) is 778, and FY19 total quantity is 444.

FiscalYear.@footnote: The FY15 production contract award has been moved to August 2015 to align with the anticipated Full Rate Production decision in June 2015.  To prevent production gap, the program will procure critical parts in March 2015 for use in the FY15 Production contract.
FY16 is the second Lot of Full Rate Production Block II missiles.

Name.@footnote: CATM unit cost decreases from FY15 to FY16 reflect increased quantities. CATM unit cost decreases from FY18 and to FY19 reflect decreased total missile quantities (CATM unit cost is directly affected by the large decreases of AUR's in FY19).
Name.val: 1.1.2) Captive Air Training Missile - Block II

Name.@footnote: Based on research of past trends, the program office has identified an annual Diminishing Manufacturing Sources (DMS) requirement. These funds were previously included in non-recurring engineering and encompassed obsolescence and loss of manufacturing sources for custom circuit cards related to the inertial measurement unit, control actuator system, and the missile guidance unit.

Increase in Special Tool & Test Equipment (ST/STE) from FY15 to FY16 is based on a one-time tooling update for the Block II Plus missile configuration.  FY17 and FY18 increase reflect programs 10 year update to production tooling.
Name.val: 3.1.1) Special Tool & Test Equip (ST/STE) - Block II

Name.@footnote: Containers are procured on a ratio of 4:1, plus 10% attrition in the fleet. Each container can hold up to 4 missiles.  AURs and CATMs cannot be mixed within the same container.

Production logistics support funding previously included in the Non-Recurring Engineering line has been moved to the Production Technical Support line. This includes funding to manage technical documentation, training development and delivery, production support, and management of government owned property, to support production of AIM-9X configurations.  Increase over prior year represents the programs anticipated cost to incorporate Block II plus missile configuration changes.

The training equipment line includes the Telemetry Kits used to collect flight data for production qualification testing and weapons safety evaluations.  The line includes additional requirement to qualify the Block II plus materials for support a Lot 17 cut-in decision.
